Looking at your problem, the issue is that `quote!` doesn't interpolate inside docstring comments (`///`) because they're treated as literal strings. To interpolate a type into a docstring, you need to use the `#[doc = ...]` attribute syntax. Here's a self-contained solution:

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]\nname = \"repr_discriminant_example\"\nversion = \"0.1.0\"\nedition = \"2021\"\n\n[lib]\nname = \"repr_discriminant\"\nproc-macro = true\npath = \"src/lib.rs\"\n\n[dependencies]\nsyn = { version = \"2.0\", features = [\"full\", \"extra-traits\"] }\nquote = \"1.0\"\nproc-macro2 = \"1.0\"\n\n[[bin]]\nname = \"example\"\npath = \"src/main.rs\"\n",
  "main.rs": "//! Example usage of the repr_discriminant macro\n\nuse repr_discriminant::repr_discriminant;\n\n#[repr_discriminant(u8, id)]\nenum Foo {\n    Bar(String) = 0x02,\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    let foo = Foo::Bar(\"Hello, world!\".into());\n    println!(\"{}\", foo.id());\n}\n"
}
```

To make this work, you'll also need to update your `src/lib.rs` file with the fixed macro implementation. The key change is in how we generate the docstring - we need to use `#[doc = ...]` attribute syntax with string interpolation:

```rust
// lib.rs - Fixed implementation
use proc_macro::TokenStream;
use proc_macro2::Span;
use quote::quote;
use syn::parse::{Parse, ParseStream};
use syn::token::Comma;
use syn::{parse_macro_input, Data, DeriveInput, Ident, Type};

const DEFAULT_DISCRIMINANT_METHOD_NAME: &str = "discriminant";

#[proc_macro_attribute]
pub fn repr_discriminant(args: TokenStream, input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
    let args: Args = parse_macro_input!(args);
    let typ = args.typ;
    let method_name = args
        .method_name
        .unwrap_or_else(|| Ident::new(DEFAULT_DISCRIMINANT_METHOD_NAME, Span::call_site()));
    let input: DeriveInput = parse_macro_input!(input as DeriveInput);
    let generics = &input.generics;
    let (impl_generics, ty_generics, where_clause) = generics.split_for_impl();
    let name = &input.ident;

    let body = match input.data {
        Data::Enum(_) => {
            // Convert the type to a string for the doc comment
            let typ_string = typ.to_token_stream().to_string();

            quote! {
                #[doc = "Returns the discriminant value of the enum.\n\n# Safety\n\nThis method is safe, because the macro guarantees that the enum is repr("]
                #[doc = #typ_string]
                #[doc = ")."]
                pub const fn #method_name(&self) -> #typ {
                    #[allow(unsafe_code)]
                    unsafe {
                        *::core::ptr::from_ref(self)
                            .cast::<#typ>()
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        _ => unimplemented!(),
    };

    TokenStream::from(quote! {
        #[repr(#typ)]
        #input

        impl #impl_generics #name #ty_generics #where_clause {
            #body
        }
    })
}

struct Args {
    typ: Type,
    method_name: Option<Ident>,
}

impl Parse for Args {
    fn parse(input: ParseStream<'_>) -> syn::Result<Self> {
        let typ: Type = input.parse()?;

        if input.is_empty() {
            return Ok(Self {
                typ,
                method_name: None,
            });
        };

        let _: Comma = input.parse()?;
        let method_name = input.parse()?;

        if !input.is_empty() {
            return Err(input.error("Unexpected tokens after method name"));
        }

        Ok(Self {
            typ,
            method_name,
        })
    }
}
```

The key changes:
1. Convert `typ` to a string using `typ.to_token_stream().to_string()`
2. Use `#[doc = ...]` attributes with string interpolation instead of `///` comments
3. Split the docstring into multiple `#[doc = ...]` attributes to include the type in the middle

This will generate the proper docstring with the type interpolated.

